I thought at one point I read where you worked at EB... well, I worked there for a few years in management, and I have endless numbers of stories to tell, as well. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Needless to say, I worked at some of the more &quot;out in the woods&quot; type EB's, and we were a little &quot;harder&quot; on our customers. If someone was looking around at 8:30 or so and was honestly trying to decide which item to buy at 9, I was cool with that. But if some fucktard walked in at 8:59, I had no qualms reminding them very clearly &quot;We close in about 2 minutes, so if you need some help with something really fast, let me know&quot;. Usually, I would use the age-old excuse &quot;Sorry, we have to shut the registers down in 2 minutes, and we can't have people in the store after 9:05, for insurance reasons&quot;. It always worked, and the fucktards would usually get the hint when I started turning off lights.<br>
<br>
I also loved, while working at EB, the stupid fucks who would try to return @#%$ like 6 months to a year after they bought it. You can show them the sign on the counter, you can point out the return policy ON THE @#%$ RECEIPT, but they still want to argue and fight over it. People will try to take advantage of you, if they can. <br>
<br>
Then you have your folks who are the &quot;habitual refunders&quot;, they buy something once a week and ALWAYS, WITHOUT FAIL, return it that same week. It used to be worse back in the floppy-disk days, but still bad now with CD burners and stuff. There was one guy I remember, I even STILL remember his NAME, he'd buy something on the weekend, and ALWAYS return it that same Friday. Then when you try to explain after the 20th return that you refuse service to them, they want to argue about it and talk to your DM and take you to court, etc. <br>
<br>
I worked at Barnes and Noble, too, and you'd get some chumps who would want to sit in the store for awhile after close, having the whole place to themselves. They, too, got the hint when the lights started going out. <br>
<br>
It's amazing that most of the &quot;best&quot; customers are the ones who've worked retail at some point in their lives. People are such rude, inconsiderate bastards the moment they walk into a retail store. This is AMERICA. The Customer is Always Right policy went out the window about 20 years ago. Spending an evening shopping in the mall and just observing people as customers is enough to make a mature person very, very ill. People who have &quot;been in the store clerk's shoes&quot; are usually the ones who are better able to empathize with the 17 year old salesperson making minimum wage to get enough money to go to school or get their first car. <br>
<br>
The most FUN I ever had in retail over the years, though, was catching shoplifters. What a bunch of stupid-fucks. The funniest part about it was that they ALWAYS were pissed at you for catching them. Sad thing is, if they were just a LITTLE intelligent, they'd get away with it most of the time.<br>
<br>
i.e. When the Sega Saturn came out, we had floor-displays DANGEROUSLY close to the entrance. Sure enough, one day, a very busy day, I noticed the stack getting &quot;smaller&quot; yet we hadn't recorded any sales, and none of the group of customers in the store were walking around carrying one. Well, while reporting it to mall security, while I was on the phone, here comes this shady character and his pal (the distracter, of course), and the distracter starts asking me lots of rapid-fire, stupid questions. JUST as his partner is walking out with the next game system, the mall security guy walks down our section of the mall and nods to me, following the other guy out to his car. Needless to say, this pair was caught red-handed. The funnier part of the story was that the pair had THREE Sega Saturns in their car, along with stolen merchandise from three other mall stores, a local Wal-Mart, and a local Sears store. Can you spell &quot;FELONY&quot;, boys and girls? I had to go out and ID the two, and both started calling me names and stuff, which only made me laugh, which only pissed them off more, etc. <br>
<br>
I have a whole new respect for retail folks, as well as fast-food workers... ah, fast-food workers! But those are other stories for another time. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Bul<br>
